listed on the slide, but beyond that, I think I want to start off with saying

92
00:05:35.500 --> 00:05:39.360
that the early phase trials form the foundation for the path of clinical

93
00:05:39.420 --> 00:05:43.360
trial development, right? It is the first step we take when we want to bring

94
00:05:43.480 --> 00:05:45.980
forward a therapy into the clinic.

95
00:05:46.420 --> 00:05:50.360
So it's very important, and that's why there is a lot of emphasis on how do

96
00:05:50.420 --> 00:05:54.300
you design these trials appropriately, especially with the changing landscape of

97
00:05:54.320 --> 00:05:58.216
treatments in cancer. So the real question becomesHow much

98
00:05:58.276 --> 00:06:02.076
information are you collecting? How informative is this information?

99
00:06:02.236 --> 00:06:06.116
And how, without hurrying up, are you using all of this information in

100
00:06:06.136 --> 00:06:07.546
an informed way to make the

101
00:06:08.616 --> 00:06:12.326
next decision? So really it's the foundation, if I can say that,

102
00:06:13.216 --> 00:06:16.876
for trials in the landscape. So

103
00:06:17.156 --> 00:06:19.616
the basic trial characteristics we all know, right?

104
00:06:19.656 --> 00:06:22.736
The goal is to identify a safe and tolerable dose,

105
00:06:23.676 --> 00:06:27.596
treating cohorts of patients at escalating dose levels, and using dose-limiting

106
00:06:27.676 --> 00:06:30.035
toxicity to really understand what's a safe dose.

107
00:06:30.436 --> 00:06:33.736
But often we probably ignore the richness of the toxicity data.

108
00:06:33.896 --> 00:06:37.336
I'll talk a little bit about it. We don't probably often spend enough time

109
00:06:37.476 --> 00:06:41.136
understanding the efficacy readout in early phase trials.

110
00:06:41.536 --> 00:06:44.276
So in the past, we were doing only dose escalation.

111
00:06:44.516 --> 00:06:47.716
Then it was called a dose expansion, but now we have a different term.

112
00:06:47.836 --> 00:06:49.776
Almost always you see in all early phase

113
00:06:50.676 --> 00:06:53.096
trials, the concept of dose optimization.

114
00:06:53.436 --> 00:06:57.256
So dose optimization really means you have identified a set of tolerable

115
00:06:57.296 --> 00:07:00.476
dose levels, but now you want to really understand a bit more.

116
00:07:00.576 --> 00:07:02.636
Like, what is the best schedule?

117
00:07:04.436 --> 00:07:08.396
Do you do a fixed dosing? Do you want to understand the mode of administration?

118
00:07:08.496 --> 00:07:12.476
Are there certain subsets of patients who may benefit or may have a better

119
00:07:12.536 --> 00:07:16.436
efficacy readout or tolerate this dose a little bit differently than

120
00:07:16.496 --> 00:07:19.396
everybody else? Then there's PRO data.

121
00:07:19.816 --> 00:07:23.496
So there's all of this additional information that you spend a little bit more time

122
00:07:23.536 --> 00:07:26.436
in early phase to actually understand. So dose optimization, right?

123
00:07:26.936 --> 00:07:28.356
So why dose optimization?

124
00:07:29.596 --> 00:07:33.196
There's multiple levels of toxicity data that's collected in phase one.

125
00:07:33.536 --> 00:07:36.496
As I always say, it's both the length and the breadth.

126
00:07:37.076 --> 00:07:41.046
So there is different types of toxicity information that you collect, and

127
00:07:41.096 --> 00:07:45.036
also how long you're treating the patient, how much cumulative toxicity

128
00:07:45.096 --> 00:07:48.916
they accumulate. So you also want to gather information on the

129
00:07:48.956 --> 00:07:52.856
delays, discontinuations, and reductions, because oftentimes the dose that you move

130
00:07:52.896 --> 00:07:56.596
from an early phase to a phase two or a phase three, you realize,

131
00:07:56.656 --> 00:08:00.016
especially because I do trials in all setting,

132
00:08:01.256 --> 00:08:05.156
you see sometimes you bring forward a dose level from a phase one and you do a

133
00:08:05.176 --> 00:08:08.876
non-inferiority in a phase three, and you have

134
00:08:08.916 --> 00:08:12.816
patients that are not able to tolerate the dose, and so they don't even stay

135
00:08:12.876 --> 00:08:14.596
on the treatment beyond one or two cycles.

136
00:08:14.916 --> 00:08:18.416
So clearly the non-inferiority margin and anything that you're trying to understand

137
00:08:18.436 --> 00:08:22.416
in a phase three, you cannot do because you just don't have the right dose that

138
00:08:22.436 --> 00:08:25.606
you're giving to the patient. So it's very important to understand the delays,

139
00:08:25.676 --> 00:08:28.776
discontinuations, interruptions, and reductions.

140
00:08:30.136 --> 00:08:33.006
And then, of course, we want to understand any of these safe doses, do they

141
00:08:33.096 --> 00:08:36.836
actually benefit the patient? What's the benefit-risk ratio?

142
00:08:37.616 --> 00:08:39.846
And are there homogeneous subgroups?

143
00:08:40.136 --> 00:08:44.036
Are there frail patients who may need a different type

144
00:08:44.096 --> 00:08:47.696
of dosing, intermittent dosing, for example? Is it histology focused?

145
00:08:47.796 --> 00:08:51.396
Is it biomarker defined? And often, we

146
00:08:51.436 --> 00:08:55.316
don't do this a lot in early phase trials, but I have, towards the end of my

147
00:08:55.796 --> 00:08:59.296
presentation, I'll try to help you understand why it's very important to also start

148
00:08:59.336 --> 00:09:03.276
to focus on patient-reported outcomes, on how are

149
00:09:03.336 --> 00:09:04.816
they perceiving

150
00:09:05.976 --> 00:09:09.696
their toxicity or efficacy that they're receiving in that treatment.

151
00:09:11.056 --> 00:09:14.816
So dose optimization all around very important because we have to identify

152
00:09:14.886 --> 00:09:18.456
doses and schedules not just for that trial, but for moving it through the clinical

153
00:09:18.516 --> 00:09:21.996
trial space. So you have to know that these doses and schedules that you're

154
00:09:22.056 --> 00:09:25.796
identifying in the early phase, they're able to tolerate long-term, it's

155
00:09:25.816 --> 00:09:29.796
improving adherence. Patients have to be compliant to be able to derive the

156
00:09:29.836 --> 00:09:32.976
benefit, and ultimately, does it improve the overall outcomes

157
00:09:33.056 --> 00:09:35.196
in terms of survival or

158
00:09:36.216 --> 00:09:37.876
other outcomes in cancer?

159
00:09:39.196 --> 00:09:42.476
So data used in dose optimization. Again, I'm going to go back.

160
00:09:42.536 --> 00:09:45.016
It's the tolerability. We don't do a great

161
00:09:46.436 --> 00:09:50.116
job today of really understanding the full spectrum of the toxicity data we

162
00:09:50.156 --> 00:09:53.476
collect on patients in phase one trials.

163
00:09:53.536 --> 00:09:56.296
How much information do we use on the relationship to the treatment?

164
00:09:56.456 --> 00:09:58.616
Do we pay attention to when the event occurs?

165
00:09:59.136 --> 00:10:00.536
What are the different types of AEs?

166
00:10:00.696 --> 00:10:03.996
Are there different grades of adverse events, the patient's experience?

167
00:10:04.296 --> 00:10:08.116
Because we almost always focus on what's called a serious adverse events, but

168
00:10:08.176 --> 00:10:11.896
we have trials where patients are dropping out, not for serious adverse events, but

169
00:10:11.956 --> 00:10:15.856
multiple mild toxicities. They're unable to take even the

170
00:10:15.876 --> 00:10:19.396
grade two rash that continues for multiple cycles, and

171
00:10:19.436 --> 00:10:20.576
they go off

172
00:10:21.436 --> 00:10:21.996
the treatment.

173
00:10:22.796 --> 00:10:24.816
And then I already spoke about this.

174
00:10:24.846 --> 00:10:28.406
And then efficacy can be clinical outcomes like progression,

175
00:10:28.876 --> 00:10:32.786
survival, tumor shrinkage, or it could be any bio-- If you have a

176
00:10:32.796 --> 00:10:35.636
good understanding of the molecular features

177
00:10:35.716 --> 00:10:39.636
of this target, maybe even understanding that at the early

178
00:10:39.736 --> 00:10:42.916
stage is important. And patient-reported outcomes, it doesn't have to be just

179
00:10:43.036 --> 00:10:46.886
quality of life, but it's also how are the patients' interpretation

180
00:10:46.936 --> 00:10:49.286
of the toxicity they are experiencing in the trial.

181
00:10:50.076 --> 00:10:51.446
That's very important because

182
00:10:52.436 --> 00:10:55.416
most of what we have talked about designs are really

183
00:10:55.776 --> 00:10:57.556
clinician-assessed adverse events.

184
00:10:57.576 --> 00:10:59.876
When a patient presents to you in the clinic.

185
00:11:00.276 --> 00:11:04.096
But really there's a patient perception of these, the PRO CTCAEs,

186
00:11:04.396 --> 00:11:08.216
which it was

187
00:11:08.256 --> 00:11:12.056
somewhat in its nascency before, but now it's widely used, at least in the late

188
00:11:12.096 --> 00:11:15.916
phase trials. And I think there is a space for bringing it to earlier phase

189
00:11:15.956 --> 00:11:16.396
trials.

190
00:11:17.196 --> 00:11:19.296
So focusing on adverse events, very simple.

191
00:11:19.856 --> 00:11:23.836
If you don't want to even focus on, okay, are there certain adverse events

192
00:11:23.936 --> 00:11:27.226
I want to focus on in the early phase trial, or do I want to look at the whole

193
00:11:27.356 --> 00:11:28.856
spectrum of adverse? So it's very simple.

194
00:11:28.896 --> 00:11:32.876
So you really just take everything that the patient experiences in a cycle

195
00:11:33.056 --> 00:11:36.486
and you just compute a score. And however long they are on treatment,

196
00:11:37.256 --> 00:11:40.916
you can either do a total or you can do an average, depending on number of

197
00:11:40.956 --> 00:11:42.796
cycles that they take.

198
00:11:43.336 --> 00:11:46.776
The only downfall of this is

199
00:11:47.436 --> 00:11:49.256
how do I weight the different toxicities?

200
00:11:49.296 --> 00:11:52.446
You grade them today with the CTCAs, maybe just use the grade.

201
00:11:53.136 --> 00:11:56.976
So it's not very difficult to come up with a score

202
00:11:57.076 --> 00:12:00.476
that actually is encompassing all of their toxicity

203
00:12:00.496 --> 00:12:04.272
experience in the early phase setting.So then you

204
00:12:05.592 --> 00:12:08.092
can figure out what a worse score should be, right?

205
00:12:08.192 --> 00:12:11.272
Everything that's grade four or grade five, so you can normalize those scores.

206
00:12:11.332 --> 00:12:13.562
It's not difficult to do all of that.

207
00:12:14.402 --> 00:12:17.392
Then you do a total toxicity profile. It's zero to one.

208
00:12:17.552 --> 00:12:21.542
It incorporates, like I said, the length and breadth, the different types, and how

209
00:12:21.572 --> 00:12:24.892
long they are on treatment, multiple cycles of treatment, multiple grades, multiple

210
00:12:24.972 --> 00:12:26.912
types, everything into the score.

211
00:12:27.912 --> 00:12:31.752
And then you create two sub-models, one for toxicity, which is really our

212
00:12:31.772 --> 00:12:34.532
dose escalation phase. Obviously, our first and foremost

213
00:12:36.012 --> 00:12:39.672
outcome in a dose-finding or an early phase trial is to make sure it's safe.

214
00:12:39.732 --> 00:12:42.572
So definitely the dose escalation phase goes first, because if the

215
00:12:42.612 --> 00:12:46.032
treatment is not even tolerable, we don't want to go

216
00:12:46.292 --> 00:12:48.932
anywhere beyond. It doesn't matter if it's efficacious, right?

217
00:12:49.012 --> 00:12:52.952
If we can't tolerate it. So then you have the efficacy model for

218
00:12:53.072 --> 00:12:56.872
the dose optimization. And then you identify the doses that are both safe

219
00:12:56.992 --> 00:12:57.552
and

220
00:12:59.092 --> 00:13:02.872
provide some sort of a benefit-risk ratio for the patient.

221
00:13:02.932 --> 00:13:06.132
So we can incorporate data from multiple treatment cycles.

222
00:13:06.252 --> 00:13:10.072
We can look at continuous efficacy outcome, could be quality of life,

223
00:13:10.232 --> 00:13:13.872
clinical biomarker. You can incorporate mild, moderate toxicities.

224
00:13:13.882 --> 00:13:15.552
You can incorporate late toxicities.

225
00:13:15.912 --> 00:13:18.392
You can incorporate all of this information.

226
00:13:19.652 --> 00:13:23.592
So simple, right? Most of us, when we think of phase one trials

227
00:13:23.612 --> 00:13:26.672
and if you think of our regular three plus three. Okay.

228
00:13:26.732 --> 00:13:30.032
So one out of three patients, I want to add three more patients, two out of six.

229
00:13:30.752 --> 00:13:34.192
What do I say? Very algorithmic designs.

230
00:13:34.262 --> 00:13:38.012
But even here, you want to know what a toxicity threshold has to be, right?

231
00:13:38.072 --> 00:13:39.932
You can't come in with a score and say, "Now what

232
00:13:40.832 --> 00:13:44.032
does 0.28 mean?" So, we have to think about

233
00:13:44.792 --> 00:13:48.732
what's the worst experience a patient can have for this particular

234
00:13:48.852 --> 00:13:52.792
regimen, and we can come up with a score, between zero and one, that

235
00:13:52.852 --> 00:13:56.392
we think is not tolerable. I just put 0.28. You can do 0.35, 0.5.

236
00:13:56.552 --> 00:14:00.492
Depends on if this is in a hematologic setting and

237
00:14:00.512 --> 00:14:04.192
they have a lot of heme adverse events, maybe you don't want to consider that.

238
00:14:04.242 --> 00:14:07.252
Maybe you only consider the non-heme adverse events, and then you can come up with

239
00:14:07.312 --> 00:14:11.292
a score. So there's many ways to develop this score. Now that's the score.

240
00:14:11.492 --> 00:14:15.292
And then over time, like I was saying, every patient, we don't just give one

241
00:14:15.332 --> 00:14:18.122
cycle of treatment to the patient when they get onto the phase twos and the phase

242
00:14:18.192 --> 00:14:20.872
threes. They are exposed to multiple cycles of treatment.

243
00:14:21.292 --> 00:14:25.092
